{"id": "26658", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=26658", "title": "Deceiver", "text": "Deceivers\u00a0(a.k.a. Veiled Demons, Doom Vipers, or Snake Demons) are a type of &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;\nLore.\nDeceivers are the favored servants of &lt;a href=\"Belial\"&gt;Belial&lt;/a&gt;, who granted them some of his skill in cunning and illusion. Deceivers will cloak themselves in the familiar forms of their enemy's companions and friends, waiting to strike when the moment is opportune. It is only then that their true forms are revealed. Deceivers have been stated to 'drain the minds' of those around them, allowing them to fuel their illusions. They carry two-pronged weapons that can quickly rip a target to pieces. The metal used in these tridents is freezing cold to touch.\nDeceivers have genders.\nA number of Deceivers serve &lt;a href=\"Aeshama\"&gt;Aeshama&lt;/a&gt;, guarding her &lt;a href=\"Domain%20of%20Horror\"&gt;Domain of Horror&lt;/a&gt;.\nDuring the &lt;a href=\"End%20of%20Days\"&gt;End of Days&lt;/a&gt;, Deceivers were used in bulk, either replacing members of &lt;a href=\"Caldeum\"&gt;Caldeum&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"Imperial%20Guard\"&gt;Imperial Guard&lt;/a&gt;, or becoming the Guard itself.\nIn-game.\nDiablo Immortal.\nDeceivers are encountered in the &lt;a href=\"Domain%20of%20Horror\"&gt;Domain of Horror&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". They can summon &lt;a href=\"Serpent%20Totem\"&gt;Serpent Totem&lt;/a&gt;s.\nDiablo III.\nDeveivers are encountered in of\u00a0\"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\".\u00a0They are Belial's personal guard, agents and the bulk of his army.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Adventure%20Mode\"&gt;Adventure Mode&lt;/a&gt;, their weaker variants called &lt;a href=\"Abyssal\"&gt;Abyssal&lt;/a&gt;s can be encountered.\nThere are two types of Deceivers in \"Diablo III\":\nDeceivers.\nLike Belial himself, Deceivers are capable of taking any form, disguising themselves as &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt;s. The player first encounters them when they enter the &lt;a href=\"Khasim%20Outpost\"&gt;Khasim Outpost&lt;/a&gt;, where a bunch of Deceivers led by &lt;a href=\"Maghda\"&gt;Maghda&lt;/a&gt; are impersonating the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Wolves\"&gt;Iron Wolves&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Imperial%20Guard\"&gt;Imperial Guard&lt;/a&gt;. As soon as their deception is disclosed, they transform back into their original forms, and are to be fought. Later in game, most Deceivers will either attack the player openly or throw their disguise of Imperial Guardsmen (whose ranks, most likely, consist entirely\u00a0of Belial's demons), or sometimes regular citizens, at the sight of the player.\u00a0\nIn addition to that, Deceivers may appear out of nowhere (for scripted events), and their most dangerous skill is invisibility. When they are away from player (not in close combat), they may vanish, becoming invisible (only slight ripple in the air betrays their location) for roughly 3 seconds. In this form, they are impervious to damage, and the first melee hit they deliver will deal double damage, ending the effect. Being ninja-stabbed by multiple Deceivers can prove deadly for an average hero. Fortunately, while they are locked in close combat, they cannot enter invisibility again.\nSerpent Magi.\nSerpent Magi are lacking melee attack (technically they can use it, but will not do so willingly), and may not turn invisible (but may appear out of nowhere or take forms of humans). In return, they create a circular Lightning field around themselves (must stay immobile to channel it) that causes increasing ticks of Lightning damage. Several fields in one area stack. Their goal is to make players flee so that Deceivers may enter invisibility again."}
{"id": "33073", "revid": "3551649", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=33073", "title": "Deceivers' Orders", "text": "Deceivers' Orders is a three-part &lt;a href=\"Tomes\"&gt;tome&lt;/a&gt; found in of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It is found on the corpses of Envoys of &lt;a href=\"Belial\"&gt;Belial&lt;/a&gt; in various locations. They form part of the \"Eavesdropper\" achievement.\nThe parts read as follows:\nPart I (&lt;a href=\"Sewers%20of%20Caldeum\"&gt;Sewers of Caldeum&lt;/a&gt;).\n\"My exemplary servants,\"\n\"Keep &lt;a href=\"Adria\"&gt;the witch&lt;/a&gt; alive until she talks. Pain will loose her tongue, but only to a point. Remember what happened with the vizier's assistant...? It was a pleasurable time, I admit, but the man had only incoherent babble and bloody strands of pus spilling from his lips by the end. \u2014 Belial\"\nPart II (&lt;a href=\"Dahlgur%20Oasis\"&gt;Dahlgur Oasis&lt;/a&gt;).\n\"Overwhelm &lt;a href=\"the%20Nephalem\"&gt;the enemy&lt;/a&gt; and seize his/her companions. There is a witch among them and... another... &lt;a href=\"Leah\"&gt;a girl&lt;/a&gt;. Bring them to me along with the &lt;a href=\"Black%20Soulstone\"&gt;Black Soulstone&lt;/a&gt;. They will be searching for the head of &lt;a href=\"Zoltun%20Kulle\"&gt;Zoltun Kulle&lt;/a&gt;. Scour the oasis for it. Some old sorcery lingers on the skull, and it must be mine. \u2014 Belial\"\nPart III (&lt;a href=\"Desolate%20Sands\"&gt;Desolate Sands&lt;/a&gt;).\n\"Miserable wretches,\"\n\"I have no time for your excuses. &lt;a href=\"Caldeum\"&gt;Caldeum&lt;/a&gt; is on the brink of rebellion, and the enemy is closing in on the &lt;a href=\"archives%20of%20Zoltun%20Kulle\"&gt;archives of Zoltun Kulle&lt;/a&gt;. Slaughter him/her and bring me the mad wizard's head and the Black Soulstone, or I shall inflict incomprehensible agony upon the lot of you. \u2014 Belial\""}
