{"id": "6460", "revid": "5104557", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6460", "title": "Moser's Blessed Circle", "text": "Moser's Blessed Circle is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Round%20Shield\"&gt;Round Shield&lt;/a&gt; from \"\".\nAlthough not as high chance of &lt;a href=\"block\"&gt;block&lt;/a&gt;ing as a &lt;a href=\"Shields\"&gt;shield&lt;/a&gt; such as &lt;a href=\"Visceratuant\"&gt;Visceratuant&lt;/a&gt;, Moser's Blessed Circle does boast a high defense along with some other useful properties.\nFor one thing, Moser's Blessed Circle offers an increased Block Rate, which certain shields don't offer. However, most notable is the boost to &lt;a href=\"Resistances\"&gt;Resistances&lt;/a&gt; that Moser's Blessed Circle has. Most small shields, although they have high chances of blocking, do not have the resistances that Moser's Blessed Circle does.\nMoser's Blessed Circle is socketed. Therefore, a character can have a variety of customizations with it. One could add perfect &lt;a href=\"Diamond\"&gt;Diamond&lt;/a&gt;s to it, further increasing its resistances or customize it with other ways via\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Runes\"&gt;Runes&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Jewel\"&gt;Jewel&lt;/a&gt;s, and other &lt;a href=\"gems\"&gt;gems&lt;/a&gt;.\nMoser's Blessed Circle is a versatile shield- certainly not specific to &lt;a href=\"classes\"&gt;classes&lt;/a&gt;, its sockets make it customizable to whatever its user wants.\nStats.\nDefense: 156-179\nRequired Level: 31\nRequired Strength: 53\nDurability: 64\nChance to Block:\nPaladin &lt;a href=\"Smite\"&gt;Smite&lt;/a&gt; Damage: 7 To 14"}
{"id": "37520", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37520", "title": "Mosquito", "text": "The Mosquito is a type of enemy encountered in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". They are encountered on &lt;a href=\"Bilefen\"&gt;Bilefen&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "3461", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3461", "title": "Mosquito Demon", "text": "Mosquito Demons (or sometimes called Suckers) have a chance to drain their victims' &lt;a href=\"mana\"&gt;mana&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"stamina\"&gt;stamina&lt;/a&gt;. Though they are not particularly deadly, they can be annoying as they tend to &lt;a href=\"poison\"&gt;poison&lt;/a&gt; on contact and leave players without stamina. \nLuckily, one or two weapon blows should be enough to take them out. \nMosquito Demons have four variants:\nOn &lt;a href=\"Hell%20difficulty\"&gt;Hell difficulty&lt;/a&gt;, all types are &lt;a href=\"immune\"&gt;immune&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt;. Their variants have a 60/80/70/90% chance respectively to drain stamina on &lt;a href=\"Normal%20%28difficulty%29\"&gt;Normal&lt;/a&gt;, and 100% chance to drain stamina on &lt;a href=\"Nightmare%20%28difficulty%29\"&gt;Nightmare&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Hell%20%28difficulty%29\"&gt;Hell&lt;/a&gt;.\nBackground.\nThe wet, humid atmosphere of the &lt;a href=\"Kehjistan\"&gt;Kehjistan&lt;/a&gt; rainforest is an environment perfect for fly and mosquito larvae. Pools of stagnant water gather after the frequent rain storms, providing excellent spots for the adults of these species to lay their eggs. Some of the mosquitoes found here are enormous, with wingspans as large as four feet. Luckily, the larger species are also much more rarely encountered than their smaller cousins.\nGiant mosquitoes, referred to locally as \"suckers,\" are known disease carriers. Their large size makes them appropriate targets for hand or missile weapons. These insects can quickly drain the blood from a victim, causing a quick loss of stamina, making escape extremely difficult. By themselves, Suckers are not usually deadly. However, if other threats lurk nearby, Suckers will drain a victim's stamina while other creatures move in for the kill.\nSuckers' hunger for mammal blood is well known throughout the villages of Kehjistan Jungle as they tend to suck the blood out of unwary or wounded creatures the point of total withering. Despite their voracious reputation these over-sized mosquito demons are only lethal when encountered in large numbers and are normally easy to hit even with ranged weapons. A vivid and well armored hero suffers usually only &lt;a href=\"stamina\"&gt;stamina&lt;/a&gt; loss and becomes slightly fatigued if the Sucker has a chance to sting."}
{"id": "40092", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=40092", "title": "Mosquito Nest", "text": "Sucker Nests are an unused monster type from \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\". They spawn all four &lt;a href=\"Mosquito%20Demon\"&gt;Giant Mosquito&lt;/a&gt;. In the game beta they were set to levels and Acts of the normal varieties at the time of Pre-Release, also Blood Hooks had bigger levels than Feeder, while Blood Hooks are a lesser rank in the final game.\nThey can be placed in the game if given stats from another monster (or your own), and work perfectly. They don't have any color palette. Levels are in the monstats.txt to the version 1.09d, while the Names, Speed and Size are in the recent monstats.txt. \nBeta Levels.\nA list showing what locations from beta levels.txt have the same exact levels as Mosquito Nests back then (The most likely locations they were planned for are the first in each line):"}
